						<div id="siteNotice"><!-- CentralNotice --></div>
						<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading" lang="en"><span dir="auto">inode</span></h1>
						<div id="bodyContent">
								<div id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>
								<div id="contentSub"></div>
												<div id="jump-to-nav" class="mw-jump">
					Jump to:					<a href="#mw-navigation">navigation</a>, 					<a href="#p-search">search</a>
				</div>
				<div id="mw-content-text" lang="en" dir="ltr" class="mw-content-ltr"><p>In a <a href="Unix_filesystem.html" title="Unix filesystem">Unix-style file system</a>, an index node, informally referred to as an i-node, is a <a href="Data_structure.html" title="Data structure">data structure</a> used to represent a filesystem object, which can be one of various things including a file or a directory. Each i-node stores the attributes and disk block location(s) of the filesystem object's data.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Filesystem object attributes may include manipulation <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metadata" title="Metadata">metadata</a> (e.g. creation, access, modify time), as well as owner and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system_permissions" title="File system permissions">permission</a> data (e.g. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Group_identifier" title="Group identifier">group-id</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/User_identifier" title="User identifier">user-id</a>, <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system_permissions" title="File system permissions">permissions</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>A <a href="Linux.html" title="Linux">Linux</a> directory lists other filesystem objects by name, normally identifying the listed object by referring to its inode. The directory contains an entry for itself, its parent, and each of its children.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
